    <text>
        <body>
            <head>171. Memorandum From <persName corresp="recSL4LMg1w3nFIv6">William
                    Quandt</persName> of the <orgName corresp="recft7WGb7Fww0wma">National Security
                    Council</orgName> Staff to the President’s Assistant for National Security
                Affairs (<persName corresp="rectQC2yY4UhXLeKu">Brzezinski</persName>)<note n="1"
                    place="foot" type="source" xml:id="d171fn1">Source: Carter Library, National
                    Security Affairs, Brzezinski Material, Country File, Box 55, Morocco: 1–8/79.
                    Secret. Sent for information. <persName corresp="rectQC2yY4UhXLeKu"
                        >Brzezinski</persName> drew an arrow pointing to <persName
                        corresp="recSL4LMg1w3nFIv6">Quandt</persName>’s name and wrote: “Can you
                    give me a memo to <orgName corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl">State</orgName> along the
                    lines you outline? ZB. 5–1–79.”</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1979-05-01"
                        >May 1, 1979</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <list type="subject">
                <head>SUBJECT</head>
                <item>
                    <placeName corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl">Morocco</placeName> (U)</item>
            </list>
            <p>The <gloss target="#t_NIE_1">NIE</gloss> on <placeName corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl"
                    >Morocco</placeName> does indeed paint a rather bleak picture, but it is not
                totally convincing.<note n="2" place="foot" xml:id="d171fn2">Not found.</note>
                First, when there are interagency disagreements, the reasoning leading to different
                assessments is not spelled out. Second, we are seeing a post-<placeName
                    corresp="recce2VRC74PP1qXq">Iran</placeName> tendency at <gloss
                    target="#t_CIA_1">
                    <orgName corresp="recrGZfmTCYX9A5jf">CIA</orgName>
                </gloss> to go on record with pessimistic assessments in order to blunt future
                criticism of complacency. Nonetheless, not all is well in <placeName
                    corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl">Morocco</placeName>. (S)</p>
            <p>What can we do? Only a limited amount, I fear. Some of the King’s problems are of his
                own making. Others require long-term solutions. Briefly, <hi
                    rendition="simple_italic">
                    <persName corresp="rec8m8MetQlvwXVeh">Hassan</persName>’s rule is threatened by
                    the following:</hi>
            </p>
            <p>—<hi rendition="simple_italic">The <placeName corresp="recGZlEaPYk6Kf3qK"
                        >Sahara</placeName> war</hi>. It has been dragging on with no signs of
                success. No one believes a pure military victory is possible, but <persName
                    corresp="rec8m8MetQlvwXVeh">Hassan</persName> shows little willingness to accept
                a political compromise. Even if we do liberalize our <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="rec9ptkWICFUk7Mvu">arms transfer</rs> policy, we will not be able to
                help turn things around in the <placeName corresp="recGZlEaPYk6Kf3qK"
                    >Sahara</placeName>. We might, in fact, encourage <persName
                    corresp="rec8m8MetQlvwXVeh">Hassan</persName> to conclude that the military
                option is viable. (S)</p>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic">Recommendation:</hi> On a case-by-case basis, we
                should continue to approve some Moroccan <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="rec9ptkWICFUk7Mvu">arms</rs> requests; we should encourage <orgName
                    corresp="recAXl1eLE0USmC6Z">Senate</orgName> efforts to restore <gloss
                    target="#t_FMS_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recM6MmQNEwIZpchW">FMS</rs>
                </gloss> for <placeName corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl">Morocco</placeName> to the full
                $40 million that we requested; but we should not have illusions that these steps
                will significantly improve <persName corresp="rec8m8MetQlvwXVeh">Hassan</persName>’s
                position. (S)</p>
            <p>—<hi rendition="simple_italic">Economy</hi>. The economic downturn is serious and is
                hurting <persName corresp="rec8m8MetQlvwXVeh">Hassan</persName>. <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="reclnawDbQgAFDvnc">Phosphate</rs> prices are low, the economy is not
                very well managed; corruption is rampant; and the <placeName
                    corresp="recXEA0LEpEd93tFt">Saudis</placeName> have cut off aid, largely because
                they could not keep track of where it was going. More money from us will not do much
                good, but the <placeName corresp="recXEA0LEpEd93tFt">Saudis</placeName> could help.
                (S)</p>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic">Recommendation:</hi> That we approach the <placeName
                    corresp="recXEA0LEpEd93tFt">Saudis</placeName> to discuss the situation in
                    <placeName corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl">Morocco</placeName> and ways in which
                    <placeName corresp="recXEA0LEpEd93tFt">Saudi Arabia</placeName> could help. King
                    <persName corresp="recsnjjizYl1z2vCL">Khalid</persName> is reportedly planning
                to visit <placeName corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl">Morocco</placeName> later this
                month. (S)</p>
            <pb facs="0441" n="420" xml:id="pg_420"/>
            <p>—<hi rendition="simple_italic">Leadership</hi>. [<hi rendition="simple_italic">less
                    than 1 line not declassified</hi>] and many of his advisers are corrupt and
                incompetent. Not much we can do here to help. (S)</p>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic">Recommendation:</hi> That our Ambassador find some
                occasion to discuss with King <persName corresp="rec8m8MetQlvwXVeh"
                    >Hassan</persName> the lessons learned from <placeName
                    corresp="recce2VRC74PP1qXq">Iran</placeName>, with emphasis on corruption and
                lack of responsiveness to demands for social change as prominent themes. <persName
                    corresp="rec8m8MetQlvwXVeh">Hassan</persName> is smart enough to get the point,
                even if he is unwilling to do much about it. (S)</p>
            <p>Finally, we have been quietly exploring whether there is some way to encourage a
                political solution to the <placeName corresp="recGZlEaPYk6Kf3qK">Sahara</placeName>
                conflict. <orgName corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl">State</orgName>’s status report is at
                    <hi rendition="simple_italic">Tab A</hi>.<note n="3" place="foot"
                    xml:id="d171fn3">Not attached.</note> We have also just heard that the
                    <placeName corresp="recXEA0LEpEd93tFt">Saudis</placeName> are prepared to help
                find a solution, which would be very encouraging. There are distinct limits on how
                much we can expect to do to mediate the <placeName corresp="recGZlEaPYk6Kf3qK"
                    >Sahara</placeName> conflict, but some of our friends could do more. <hi
                    rendition="simple_italic">In short</hi>, <persName corresp="rec8m8MetQlvwXVeh"
                    >Hassan</persName>’s problems are largely of his own making; the situation is
                serious, but probably not desperate; we have limited direct influence. (S)</p>
        </body>
    </text>
